Each time you call ```Serial.read()```, it reads the first char in the buffer. Let&#39;s say you have a ```&#39;B&#39;``` in your buffer. Unless your program happens to be at ```if (Serial.read() == &#39;B&#39;)```, it doesn&#39;t trigger the action you want. You should store a returned value from ```Serial.read()``` and evaluate it.

```c++
void loop()  {

  char c = Serial.read();

  if (c == &#39;F&#39;) {
    Serial.println(&quot;F!&quot;);
  }

  if (c == &#39;B&#39;) {
    Serial.println(&quot;B!&quot;);
  }

  if (c == &#39;L&#39;) {
    Serial.println(&quot;L!&quot;);
  }

  if (c == &#39;R&#39;) {
    Serial.println(&quot;R!&quot;);
  }
  
  if (c == &#39;S&#39;) {
    Serial.println(&quot;S!&quot;);
  }
}
```

